body:
# GitHub Webhooks

Webhooks deliver real-time HTTP POST notifications to your server when events occur on GitHub. When a push, pull request, issue, or other event happens, GitHub sends a JSON payload to your configured URL. This enables event-driven automation without polling the API.

## Creating a Webhook

```javascript
import { Octokit } from "@octokit/rest";

const octokit = new Octokit({ auth: process.env.GITHUB_TOKEN });

const { data: hook } = await octokit.repos.createWebhook({
  owner: "my-org",
  repo: "my-project",
  config: {
    url: "https://my-server.com/webhooks/github",
    content_type: "json",
    secret: process.env.WEBHOOK_SECRET,
    insecure_ssl: "0",
  },
  events: ["push", "pull_request", "issues"],
  active: true,
});
console.log(hook.id, hook.active, hook.events);
```

```bash
# Create webhook via gh CLI
gh api repos/owner/repo/hooks -X POST \
  --input - <<EOF
{
  "config": {
    "url": "https://my-server.com/webhooks/github",
    "content_type": "json",
    "secret": "my-webhook-secret"
  },
  "events": ["push", "pull_request"],
  "active": true
}
EOF
```

## Common Events

| Event | Fires When |
|-------|------------|
| `push` | Commits pushed to a branch |
| `pull_request` | PR opened, closed, merged, or updated |
| `issues` | Issue created, edited, labeled, or closed |
| `create` | Branch or tag created |
| `delete` | Branch or tag deleted |
| `release` | Release published |
| `workflow_run` | Actions workflow run completes |
| `star` | Repository starred |
| `fork` | Repository forked |
| `ping` | Webhook created (test event) |
| `check_run` | Check run created or completed |
| `deployment` | Deployment created |
| `deployment_status` | Deployment status updated |

## Payload Format

Every webhook delivery includes:

```http
POST /webhooks/github HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/json
X-GitHub-Event: push
X-GitHub-Delivery: 72d3162e-cc78-11e3-81ab-4c9367dc0958
X-Hub-Signature-256: sha256=abc123...
User-Agent: GitHub-Hookshot/abc123

{
  "action": "opened",
  "repository": { "full_name": "my-org/my-project" },
  "sender": { "login": "developer-1" },
  ...
}
```

## Signature Verification

Always verify webhook signatures to ensure payloads come from GitHub:

```javascript
import crypto from "crypto";

function verifySignature(payload, signature, secret) {
  const expected = "sha256=" + crypto
    .createHmac("sha256", secret)
    .update(payload)
    .digest("hex");
  return crypto.timingSafeEqual(
    Buffer.from(signature),
    Buffer.from(expected)
  );
}

// In your Express handler
app.post("/webhooks/github", (req, res) => {
  const sig = req.headers["x-hub-signature-256"];
  if (!verifySignature(JSON.stringify(req.body), sig, process.env.WEBHOOK_SECRET)) {
    return res.status(401).send("Invalid signature");
  }
  const event = req.headers["x-github-event"];
  // Handle event...
  res.status(200).send("OK");
});
```

## Octokit Webhooks Library

```javascript
import { Webhooks } from "@octokit/webhooks";

const webhooks = new Webhooks({ secret: process.env.WEBHOOK_SECRET });

webhooks.on("push", ({ payload }) => {
  console.log(`Push to ${payload.ref} by ${payload.pusher.name}`);
});

webhooks.on("pull_request.opened", ({ payload }) => {
  console.log(`PR #${payload.number}: ${payload.pull_request.title}`);
});

webhooks.on("issues.opened", ({ payload }) => {
  console.log(`Issue #${payload.issue.number}: ${payload.issue.title}`);
});

// Verify and handle incoming webhook
await webhooks.verifyAndReceive({
  id: req.headers["x-github-delivery"],
  name: req.headers["x-github-event"],
  signature: req.headers["x-hub-signature-256"],
  payload: JSON.stringify(req.body),
});
```

## Managing Webhooks

```javascript
// List webhooks
const { data: hooks } = await octokit.repos.listWebhooks({
  owner: "my-org",
  repo: "my-project",
});

// Update a webhook
await octokit.repos.updateWebhook({
  owner: "my-org",
  repo: "my-project",
  hook_id: hook.id,
  events: ["push", "pull_request", "issues", "release"],
  active: true,
});

// Test a webhook (redeliver the ping event)
await octokit.repos.pingWebhook({
  owner: "my-org",
  repo: "my-project",
  hook_id: hook.id,
});

// Delete a webhook
await octokit.repos.deleteWebhook({
  owner: "my-org",
  repo: "my-project",
  hook_id: hook.id,
});
```

## Best Practices

1. **Always verify signatures** — reject requests without valid `X-Hub-Signature-256`
2. **Respond quickly** — return 200 within 10 seconds; queue heavy processing
3. **Handle redeliveries** — use `X-GitHub-Delivery` header for idempotency
4. **Use HTTPS** — webhook URLs must be publicly accessible over HTTPS
5. **Subscribe selectively** — only subscribe to events you handle
6. **Monitor deliveries** — check webhook delivery logs in repo Settings > Webhooks
